  "A TV station asks viewers to call in and vote on whether a new city tax should be enacted. Of 15,000 callers, 78% oppose the tax. What type of bias most likely affects this result?": "",
  "Recall bias": "",
  "Voluntary response bias": "",
  "Interviewer bias": "",
  "Call-in polls attract people with strong opinions; those opposed to taxes are more motivated to call, producing voluntary response bias.": "",
  "A survey asks: 'Don't you agree that our school's outstanding cafeteria deserves more funding?' Out of 200 respondents, 85% agree. What type of bias is present?": "",
  "Survivorship bias": "",
  "Response bias from a leading question": "",
  "Nonresponse bias": "",
  "The question uses loaded language ('outstanding cafeteria') and a leading structure ('Don't you agree...'), pushing respondents toward agreement.": "",
  "A researcher mails surveys to 2,000 households but only 300 return them. She finds that 60% of respondents support a policy. If nonrespondents tend to be younger and less supportive, how is the result affected?": "",
  "The 60% likely overestimates true support due to nonresponse bias": "",
  "The 60% likely underestimates true support": "",
  "Nonresponse has no effect on the estimate": "",
  "The 60% is accurate because 300 is a large enough sample": "",
  "With only a 15% response rate and younger, less-supportive people not responding, the sample over-represents supporters, so 60% is likely an overestimate.": "",
  "A phone survey about internet usage only uses landline numbers. Critics point out that younger adults who use only cell phones are excluded. What type of bias does this illustrate?": "",
  "Undercoverage (a form of selection bias)": "",
  "Cell-phone-only households are systematically excluded from the sampling frame, which is undercoverage -- a form of selection bias.": "",
  "A health study asks participants to report how many alcoholic drinks they consume per week. Researchers suspect the reported numbers are lower than actual consumption. What type of bias is likely at work?": "",
  "Social desirability bias": "",
  "Undercoverage bias": "",
  "Participants tend to under-report behaviors they perceive as negative (like heavy drinking) to present themselves more favorably, which is social desirability bias.": "",
  "A business magazine studies 50 successful CEOs to find common traits. They conclude that risk-taking leads to success. A statistician objects. Why?": "",
  "The magazine used cluster sampling": "",
  "50 is too small a sample": "",
  "Survivorship bias -- risk-taking CEOs who failed are not studied": "",
  "Response bias from interviews": "",
  "By studying only successful CEOs, the magazine ignores the many risk-takers who failed, creating survivorship bias and an overly positive view of risk-taking.": "",
  "A gym conducts a survey of its members about exercise habits and finds that 95% exercise at least 3 times per week. Can they generalize this to all adults in the city?": "",
